  "slug": "crostata-di-ricotta",
  "title": "Crostata di ricotta",
  "subtitle": "Italian shortcrust tart with a sweetened ricotta filling",
  "excerpt": "A classic Italian Easter tart with a crumbly pasta frolla pastry shell filled with sweetened ricotta, eggs, mixed peel, and cinnamon. The filling is richer and denser than a baked cheesecake and has a matte, slightly grainy texture from the ricotta. Finished with a lattice of pastry strips across the top. Eaten at room temperature, the tart improves in texture overnight once the ricotta sets properly.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Crostata di ricotta is documented in Italian and Neapolitan baking literature from at least the eighteenth century as an Easter preparation. Pellegrino Artusi, La Scienza in Cucina e l'Arte di Mangiar Bene (1891, freely available at Project Gutenberg IT), includes a ricotta-filled tart. The pasta frolla pastry, sweetened ricotta filling, and lattice finish are described in Italian and Neapolitan domestic cookery guides published before 1928.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The pastry for a crostata is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "pasta frolla",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Pasta frolla",
                  "termId": "cmpazy0w30000bwv412dz1q1e"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ", a rich Italian shortcrust. It is easy to mix but fragile to roll. Drain the ricotta well before using it: undrained ricotta makes the filling watery and it will not set.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
